I"v<h1 id="math">Math</h1>

<h2 id="syntax">Syntax</h2>

<div class="language-php highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="s2">"math"</span> <span class="o">=&gt;</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">boolean</span><span class="o">|</span><span class="k">array</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="nv">$value</span> <span class="c1">// default false</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<h2 id="description">Description</h2>
<p>ParsedownExtended adds the ability to use LaTeX in your markdown, by using regular expression to find and recognize LaTeX to avoid formatting it. This enables you to use a library like <a href="https://katex.org">KaTeX</a> to make the on-device rendering of the code.</p>

<h2 id="eamples">Eamples</h2>

<h3 id="enable">Enable</h3>
<p>To enable LaTeX support:</p>
<div class="language-php highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nv">$Parsedown</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="k">new</span> <span class="nc">ParsedownExtended</span><span class="p">([</span>
    <span class="s2">"math"</span> <span class="o">=&gt;</span> <span class="kc">true</span>
<span class="p">]);</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<h3 id="single-dollar-match">Single Dollar Match</h3>
<p>If you want to use single dollar to active LaTeX mode you can do the following:</p>
<div class="language-php highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nv">$Parsedown</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="k">new</span> <span class="nc">ParsedownExtended</span><span class="p">([</span>
    <span class="s2">"math"</span> <span class="o">=&gt;</span> <span class="p">[</span>
        <span class="s2">"single_dollar"</span> <span class="o">=&gt;</span> <span class="kc">true</span>
    <span class="p">]</span>
<span class="p">]);</span>
</code></pre></div></div>
